In order to tackle recursive functions, you first need to think about their base cases. Base cases are those that would not allow the function to continue forward.

In this case, we would want to check if the string is null, or empty. When we find a null, or empty string we need to return the base case, which could be an empty string itself or a warning stating that there was no capital letters found. 

Another case to check for is if the letter itself is capital. If it is capital, then return that letter.

Lastly, if we&#39;ve still got work to do (meaning there are more characters to check) then we just have to call the function again with the string starting with the next unchecked character.

    def get_first_capital(word):
